{
    "analysis": "From the previous aggregate scan: metric.csv contains many component-KPI pairs (29 distinct cmdb_id and 351 distinct kpi_name). Top metric pairs include many IG01 JVM metrics and several apache and Tomcat KPIs. trace.csv has 12 distinct cmdb_ids and 72 trace_names; IG01.trace.self.duration_mean appears in traces. log.csv covers 7 cmdb_ids and 3 log_name types (log.row_count, log.error_count, log.gc_pause_max) with Tomcat01 and apache01/02 among top entries. error_logs.csv appears empty (no error log records were returned). This suggests we should next compute global thresholds (P95) for each component-KPI / component-trace / component-log for only the candidate root-cause components list, using the full series (before any time filtering), per the diagnosis rules, and keep outputs compact (top candidates by threshold and counts).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the full CSV files (no time filtering) compute global P95 thresholds per component-series only for the allowed candidate components: [\"apache01\",\"apache02\",\"Tomcat01\",\"Tomcat02\",\"Tomcat03\",\"Tomcat04\",\"MG01\",\"MG02\",\"IG01\",\"IG02\",\"Mysql01\",\"Mysql02\",\"Redis01\",\"Redis02\"]. Do the following and return compact results (limit each to top 20 rows):\n1) metric.csv: for rows where cmdb_id is in the candidate list, aggregate by (cmdb_id, kpi_name) and compute count and global P95 of the 'value' column. Return top 20 pairs ordered by P95 descending and include columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, count, p95_value.\n2) trace.csv: for rows where cmdb_id is in the candidate list, aggregate by (cmdb_id, trace_name) and compute count and global P95 of the 'value' column. Return top 20 pairs ordered by P95 descending and include: cmdb_id, trace_name, count, p95_value.\n3) log.csv: for rows where cmdb_id is in the candidate list, aggregate by (cmdb_id, log_name) and compute count and global P95 of the 'value' column. Return top 20 pairs ordered by P95 descending and include: cmdb_id, log_name, count, p95_value.\nStore the computed thresholds in kernel variables for later steps (but only print the compact top-20 tables requested)."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the threshold tables returned: global P95 thresholds were computed for metric, trace, and log series limited to the candidate components. Notable observations from thresholds: several Redis and Tomcat memory-related metrics have extremely large P95 values (on the order of 1e9–4e9), trace row_count P95s show Tomcat services and IG/MG with high row counts, and apache/apache02 have high log.row_count P95s. These are global thresholds (computed over the full available series) as required. The next step is to detect anomalies within the incident window (March 9, 2021 18:00 to 18:30 UTC+8) by comparing metric values in that time window against their global thresholds, producing a compact summary (counts, earliest anomaly timestamp, max value, p95_value, severity ratio) per component-KPI so we can narrow candidate faults.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the kernel-stored threshold tables (metric_thresholds_df, trace_thresholds_df, log_thresholds_df) and the raw CSVs, perform anomaly detection for the incident window: March 9, 2021 from 18:00 to 18:30 (UTC+8). Do the following and return only the compact top-20 table requested:\n1) Metrics: For rows in metric.csv whose cmdb_id is in the candidate list, filter rows to the incident time window (Executor should handle timestamp-to-datetime conversion in UTC+8). Left-join each row with metric_thresholds_df on (cmdb_id, kpi_name) to obtain the global p95_value. Mark a metric row as an anomaly if value >= p95_value (ignore rows where p95_value is missing). Then aggregate anomalies by (cmdb_id, kpi_name) and compute: anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, p95_value, severity_ratio = (max_value_in_window - p95_value) / p95_value (use Inf or large number if p95_value==0). Return top 20 aggregated rows ordered first by anomaly_count desc then severity_ratio desc. Include columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, p95_value, severity_ratio. Store the full aggregated anomaly table in kernel variable metric_anomalies_df but only print the top-20 compact table.\n(Do not print raw time series; limit output rows to at most 20.)"
}

{
    "analysis": "We ran the full preprocess->threshold->anomaly-detection pipeline and discovered that the provided telemetry covers 2021-03-09 10:00–10:30 (UTC+8), not the requested incident window 18:00–18:30 — so we cannot localize a root cause for the specified 18:00–18:30 interval from these files. Using the available 10:00–10:30 data, the pipeline found no reliable high-side metric/log spikes (many metric/log p95 values are zero producing artifacts), but did find meaningful trace anomalies: notable duration spikes for Tomcat04 and Tomcat02 around ~10:05 (e.g., Tomcat04 trace.self.duration_p95 with large severity ≈6.97) and some row_count spikes for MG02/Tomcat04 at ~10:09. There are also several low-tail trace anomalies (drops) primarily involving MG nodes and some IG/Tomcat series. Given the trace duration spikes (Tomcat04, Tomcat02) are the most significant deviations, these are the best candidates for root-cause investigation in the available time window. However, we must confirm supporting evidence (metrics and logs) for those services around the anomalous timestamps before concluding a root cause. Because the 18:00–18:30 window has no telemetry here, the original request cannot be completed for that window without additional data.",
